record.text: Moving up the ladder and not writing code was the best part of my career. It forced me to zoom out and study the big picture from an angle I could not see from behind a text editor.

value.text: What bothers me in the BigTech career ladder is that it's almost expected for staff+ IC folks not to write code. Some do write it, of course, but there are some that write nothing. Pretty weird.

images.alt:
Screenshot of text:

it's my birthday today. it's also my 2 year anniversary of starting HRT (took my first dose on my bday in '22). 

i came out relatively late in life. growing up in Missouri in the 90s in a super Christian, conservative, tramautizing-beyond-the-scope-of-a-skeet home/culture, i didn't have any language to map my experience onto. nothing to explain why i was more comfortable with the girls, playing with American Girl dolls, going to ballet class. all i knew was that being gay was a thing people called me a lot, and that it was the absolute worst thing you could be as a ‚Äòman‚Äô.

as i got older this bewilderment metastasized into virulent self-hatred. something was fundamentally broken inside of me, and the only way to survive was to put on a mask, perform, and do anything to numb the pain and emptiness of that existence. i did that for so long that i forgot there was any other experience of life. i thought everybody felt that way and the world was a sick joke. i grew up to be 6‚Äô2‚Äù, broad shouldered, square jawed, smart, nice, handsome. nobody could understand the disparity between how i was perceived and how wretched i felt inside.

Screenshot of text:

as i slowly discovered what was really going on with me over the years, i made some attempts to open up. these were fiercely rejected by people who, while wonderful human beings, could not get over their conditioned disgust at seeing a ‚Äòman‚Äô express these things. it‚Äôs hard sometimes to remember that culture even 10-15 years ago was drastically different, not to mention that cultures moves unevenly. i put these parts of myself away with a fresh coat of shame, burying them deeper each time.

eventually, as my ability to keep up this performance in ever-increasing pain and confusion spiraled into complete disaster, burning my entire life to the ground, i found myself alone for the first time in my life, and during a global pandemic.

i finally went inside myself, into the basement, and let the monster out of its dungeon. i looked it in the eyes, gave it a hug, and i started transition.

Screenshot of text:

and then everything was better! üòÖ no, no unfortunately not. a lesson i‚Äôve learned the hard way is that when you‚Äôre in a deep pit, and you finally see the way out, you still have a long, long climb ahead of you. most likely with a few harrowing falls and restarts to contend with.

2 years later i‚Äôm still climbing. i struggle every day with things about my body i‚Äôll never be able to change. with regret for decades of my life spent totally lost and in pain, so far behind my peers and colleagues in so many ways. with useless yearning that my life had started completely differently.

Screenshot of text:

why am i sharing all this? well, in the US, we have an election in a few days. and on top of all this, the future of trans rights hangs in the balance. most pointedly, the rights of young people to transition. i really, really get that there‚Äôs a lot of complexity there. fear that your child may be making a mistake. a fear which is being exploited and amplified for political gain. i don‚Äôt know that i have an answer for that, but i do want to share the alternative with folks: half a life wasted in needless suffering, and permanent features of my body that will be dysphoric for the rest of my life. women like me saving up $X0,000 to have somebody saw chunks of our clavicles out and reattach them with a plate. i would give almost anything to have been able to transition when i was younger. to live in a culture  where i could see myself and understand it, a family where this was supported emotionally, and able to get the care of medical and mental health experts to help me navigate it. data shows that my situation is vastly more likely than regret. just something to consider.

record.text: it's my birthday, which is also my 2 year anniversary of starting HRT. with trans rights hanging in the balance this election, i decided to share a bit of my experience. it's all in this post so you can scroll by if you'd prefer. #trans
